00:38:19,880 --> 00:38:26,880
And we'll put the mass over here.

860
00:38:26,880 --> 00:38:28,880
All right.

861
00:38:28,880 --> 00:38:29,880
The first one, of course,

862
00:38:29,880 --> 00:38:32,880
and I'm not listing them in any particular order.

863
00:38:32,880 --> 00:38:34,380
As it happens, I am

864
00:38:34,380 --> 00:38:35,880
writing down the lightest one first.

865
00:38:35,880 --> 00:38:38,880
The lightest one is, of course, the photon.

866
00:38:38,880 --> 00:38:40,880
The standard symbol for a photon is a gamma,

867
00:38:40,880 --> 00:38:43,880
like for a gamma ray.

868
00:38:43,880 --> 00:38:46,880
It has a field associated with it.

869
00:38:46,880 --> 00:38:50,880
The gamma particle is the quantum of a field.

870
00:38:50,880 --> 00:38:53,880
In most cases, or many cases,

871
00:38:53,880 --> 00:38:58,880
the field carries the same symbol as the particle itself.

872
00:38:58,880 --> 00:39:03,880
But for the photon, the field is called A,

873
00:39:03,880 --> 00:39:05,880
and it's really the vector

874
00:39:05,880 --> 00:39:07,880
potential of the electromagnetic field.

875
00:39:07,880 --> 00:39:09,880
You could use electric or magnetic fields,

876
00:39:09,880 --> 00:39:13,880
but you can also use the vector potential,

877
00:39:13,880 --> 00:39:15,880
which is another way

878
00:39:15,880 --> 00:39:17,880
of describing the electromagnetic field.

879
00:39:17,880 --> 00:39:20,880
It has, it's a boson.

880
00:39:20,880 --> 00:39:22,880
I didn't write down the spin,

881
00:39:22,880 --> 00:39:24,880
but the spin is one unit of spin.

882
00:39:24,880 --> 00:39:26,880
The electric charge is zero.

883
00:39:26,880 --> 00:39:29,880
The baryon number, whatever that is, is zero.

884
00:39:29,880 --> 00:39:31,880
And the mass is zero.

885
00:39:31,880 --> 00:39:35,880
So that's the first particle.

886
00:39:35,880 --> 00:39:38,880
Next particle of interest is the electron.

887
00:39:38,880 --> 00:39:43,880
Now, the electron is a particle which has an antiparticle.

888
00:39:43,880 --> 00:39:45,880
It has an electric charge.

889
00:39:45,880 --> 00:39:47,880
If it has an electric charge,

890
00:39:47,880 --> 00:39:50,880
it must have an antiparticle of the opposite charge.

891
00:39:50,880 --> 00:39:52,880
And it is a convention,

892
00:39:52,880 --> 00:39:58,880
whether we think of the particle as the electron

893
00:39:58,880 --> 00:40:02,880
and the antiparticle as the positron,

894
00:40:02,880 --> 00:40:05,880
or whether we think of the positron as the particle

895
00:40:05,880 --> 00:40:07,880
and the electron as the antiparticle.

896
00:40:07,880 --> 00:40:10,880
The relation between them is mutual.

897
00:40:10,880 --> 00:40:12,880
All right, so when I write the electron,

898
00:40:12,880 --> 00:40:15,880
I really mean the electron and positron.

899
00:40:15,880 --> 00:40:20,880
And so we could write E here plus minus.

900
00:40:20,880 --> 00:40:23,880
Standing, E minus is the electron,

901
00:40:23,880 --> 00:40:25,880
E plus is the positron.

902
00:40:25,880 --> 00:40:29,880
The field of the electron is usually psi,

903
00:40:29,880 --> 00:40:32,880
and maybe you could put a little E downstairs

904
00:40:32,880 --> 00:40:34,880
to indicate that it stands for the electron.

905
00:40:34,880 --> 00:40:36,880
It's made up out of creation and annihilation,

906
00:40:36,880 --> 00:40:39,880
and annihilation operators for electrons.

907
00:40:39,880 --> 00:40:42,880
Electrons are fermions.

908
00:40:42,880 --> 00:40:44,880
It's charged, okay?

909
00:40:44,880 --> 00:40:47,880
It's charged in what units now?

910
00:40:47,880 --> 00:40:52,880
Well, the standard particle physics

911
00:40:52,880 --> 00:40:55,880
or quantum mechanical unit for electric charge,

912
00:40:55,880 --> 00:40:56,880
believe it or not,

913
00:40:56,880 --> 00:40:59,880
is the electric charge of an electron.

914
00:40:59,880 --> 00:41:01,880
It's a good unit to work in terms of.

915
00:41:01,880 --> 00:41:03,880
You can go look it up in coulombs.

916
00:41:03,880 --> 00:41:05,880
It's 10 to the minus, what?

917
00:41:06,880 --> 00:41:08,880
23 coulombs.

918
00:41:08,880 --> 00:41:11,880
10 to the minus 19th coulombs or, yeah.

919
00:41:11,880 --> 00:41:13,880
It's some very small charge.

920
00:41:13,880 --> 00:41:22,880
But it's not useful to think about it in coulombs.

921
00:41:22,880 --> 00:41:26,880
All particles in nature have electric charges

922
00:41:26,880 --> 00:41:30,880
which are integer multiples of the electron charge.

923
00:41:30,880 --> 00:41:32,880
This is not true of quarks,

924
00:41:32,880 --> 00:41:34,880
but quarks are not observable particles.

925
00:41:34,880 --> 00:41:35,880
All right.

926
00:41:35,880 --> 00:41:37,880
So the charge we'll just write

927
00:41:37,880 --> 00:41:39,880
as minus 1 for the electron

928
00:41:39,880 --> 00:41:43,880
and plus 1 for the positron.

929
00:41:43,880 --> 00:41:45,880
So since we typically think

930
00:41:45,880 --> 00:41:47,880
of the electron as a particle

931
00:41:47,880 --> 00:41:49,880
and the positron as the antiparticle,

932
00:41:49,880 --> 00:41:51,880
let's just call it minus 1

933
00:41:51,880 --> 00:41:55,880
and remember that the positron has the opposite charge.

934
00:41:55,880 --> 00:41:59,880
Baryon number is 0, and it's mass.

935
00:41:59,880 --> 00:42:03,880
Now we have to decide on units for mass.

936
00:42:03,880 --> 00:42:06,880
Units for mass are the same as units for energy.

937
00:42:06,880 --> 00:42:08,880
E equals mc squared.

938
00:42:08,880 --> 00:42:11,380
So we can either describe the

939
00:42:11,380 --> 00:42:13,880
mass as our mass in kilograms

940
00:42:13,880 --> 00:42:15,880
or in energy in joules,

941
00:42:15,880 --> 00:42:20,880
or we can simply invent a new unit

942
00:42:20,880 --> 00:42:23,380
which is more appropriate to

943
00:42:23,380 --> 00:42:25,880
microscopic physics, to atomic physics.

944
00:42:25,880 --> 00:42:28,880
In fact, the unit that we use

945
00:42:28,880 --> 00:42:31,880
comes originally historically out of atomic physics.

946
00:42:31,880 --> 00:42:36,380
It is the unit in which the ionization energy

947
00:42:36,380 --> 00:42:40,880
of an electron in a hydrogen atom is what?

948
00:42:40,880 --> 00:42:44,880
13.5 electron volts.

949
00:42:44,880 --> 00:42:46,880
An electron volt is how much energy

950
00:42:46,880 --> 00:42:48,880
you get if you pass an electron

951
00:42:48,880 --> 00:42:52,880
across a capacitor plate of one volt.

952
00:42:52,880 --> 00:42:54,880
It's a very, very small amount of

953
00:42:54,880 --> 00:42:56,880
energy, some tiny fraction of a joule.

954
00:42:56,880 --> 00:42:58,880
But one electron volt is the

955
00:42:58,880 --> 00:43:00,880
amount of energy that you get

956
00:43:00,880 --> 00:43:02,380
if you pass an electron across

957
00:43:02,380 --> 00:43:03,880
a capacitor plate of one volt.

958
00:43:03,880 --> 00:43:06,880
So the electron volt is the standard

959
00:43:06,880 --> 00:43:09,880
unit that came historically out of atomic physics,

960
00:43:09,880 --> 00:43:12,880
the theory of electrons and so forth.

961
00:43:12,880 --> 00:43:14,880
It's going to wind up being

962
00:43:14,880 --> 00:43:16,880
too small a unit for us.

963
00:43:16,880 --> 00:43:19,380
Particle physics energies are

964
00:43:19,380 --> 00:43:21,880
larger than atomic physics energies,

965
00:43:21,880 --> 00:43:24,880
but for historical reasons, we have the

966
00:43:24,880 --> 00:43:27,880
electron volt as our unit of energy,

967
00:43:27,880 --> 00:43:30,880
and the mass of an electron measured in electron volts

968
00:43:30,880 --> 00:43:32,880
is one MeV.

969
00:43:32,880 --> 00:43:34,880
In fact, it's a half an electron volt.

970
00:43:34,880 --> 00:43:36,880
Not exactly.

971
00:43:36,880 --> 00:43:40,880
I think it's 0.51 MeV,

972
00:43:40,880 --> 00:43:45,880
and MeV stands for millions of electron volts.

973
00:43:45,880 --> 00:43:47,880
An MeV will be too small

974
00:43:47,880 --> 00:43:49,880
a unit for many other purposes.

975
00:43:49,880 --> 00:43:52,880
As I said, particle physics is a mess,

976
00:43:52,880 --> 00:43:55,880
and the masses of particles extend all over the map,

977
00:43:55,880 --> 00:43:58,880
and so in trying to search for a useful unit,

978
00:43:58,880 --> 00:43:59,880
you're always frustrated.

979
00:43:59,880 --> 00:44:01,380
The useful unit will always

980
00:44:01,380 --> 00:44:02,880
be too small for the next...

981
00:44:02,880 --> 00:44:04,880
Shouldn't it be exactly a half?

982
00:44:04,880 --> 00:44:05,880
No, why?

983
00:44:09,880 --> 00:44:11,880
No, it's exactly 0.51.

984
00:44:12,880 --> 00:44:13,880
No, it's not.

985
00:44:13,880 --> 00:44:16,880
What's that?

986
00:44:16,880 --> 00:44:18,880
I mean pi 3.

987
00:44:18,880 --> 00:44:19,880
Pi 3.

988
00:44:19,880 --> 00:44:21,880
Pi equals 3.

989
00:44:21,880 --> 00:44:22,880
Pi equals 3, right.

990
00:44:22,880 --> 00:44:25,880
Okay, now, we can start...

991
00:44:25,880 --> 00:44:27,880
Quantum electrodynamics is the theory of electrons,

992
00:44:27,880 --> 00:44:29,880
and photons,

993
00:44:29,880 --> 00:44:31,880
and we've talked about it a little bit,

994
00:44:31,880 --> 00:44:33,880
more than a little bit,

995
00:44:33,880 --> 00:44:34,880
and I just...

996
00:44:34,880 --> 00:44:36,880
We could also write down over here

997
00:44:36,880 --> 00:44:38,880
a table of the various...

998
00:44:38,880 --> 00:44:39,880
We won't make it a table.

999
00:44:39,880 --> 00:44:40,880
We'll just make a...

1000
00:44:40,880 --> 00:44:42,880
We'll just draw some pictures.

1001
00:44:42,880 --> 00:44:46,880
The basic elementary process

1002
00:44:46,880 --> 00:44:49,880
that takes place in quantum electrodynamics,

1003
00:44:49,880 --> 00:44:51,880
photons and electrons,

1004
00:44:51,880 --> 00:44:55,880
is the emission of a photon by an electron.

1005
00:44:55,880 --> 00:44:56,880
Okay.

1006
00:44:57,880 --> 00:45:00,880
Electron, electron, photon,

1007
00:45:00,880 --> 00:45:02,880
and as I've showed you several times,

1008
00:45:02,880 --> 00:45:06,880
you can rearrange the legs of this diagram

1009
00:45:06,880 --> 00:45:08,880
so that this could represent

1010
00:45:08,880 --> 00:45:10,880
not the emission of a photon,

1011
00:45:10,880 --> 00:45:12,880
but the absorption of a photon.

1012
00:45:12,880 --> 00:45:15,880
A photon comes in from the past,

1013
00:45:15,880 --> 00:45:16,880
or...

1014
00:45:16,880 --> 00:45:18,880
Whoops, sorry.

1015
00:45:18,880 --> 00:45:21,880
You can even flip the electron legs around

1016
00:45:21,880 --> 00:45:23,880
so that it looks like this.

1017
00:45:25,880 --> 00:45:27,880
Electron going backward in time.

1018
00:45:27,880 --> 00:45:29,880
Well, what does that mean?

1019
00:45:29,880 --> 00:45:33,880
That really means a positron emitting a photon.

1020
00:45:33,880 --> 00:45:35,880
So the basic...

1021
00:45:37,880 --> 00:45:41,880
building block for building up processes and interactions

1022
00:45:41,880 --> 00:45:44,880
is this vertex with two electrons,

1023
00:45:44,880 --> 00:45:47,880
electron, positron, whatever coming...

1024
00:45:47,880 --> 00:45:49,880
One going in, one going out,

1025
00:45:49,880 --> 00:45:50,880
and a photon coming out of it,

1026
00:45:50,880 --> 00:45:52,880
or going into it.

1027
00:45:52,880 --> 00:45:53,880
Out of that,

1028
00:45:53,880 --> 00:45:55,880
you build up

1029
00:45:55,880 --> 00:45:56,880
all of the various processes

1030
00:45:56,880 --> 00:45:58,880
of quantum electrodynamics,

1031
00:45:58,880 --> 00:45:59,880
but in particular,

1032
00:45:59,880 --> 00:46:01,880
the process or the phenomena

1033
00:46:01,880 --> 00:46:04,880
that corresponds to the force between charges,

1034
00:46:04,880 --> 00:46:07,880
and in the language of particle exchange,

1035
00:46:07,880 --> 00:46:10,880
it's the photon bouncing back and forth

1036
00:46:10,880 --> 00:46:12,880
between charged particles,

1037
00:46:12,880 --> 00:46:15,880
which...

1038
00:46:15,880 --> 00:46:18,880
which creates that force.

1039
00:46:18,880 --> 00:46:20,880
Yet another way to describe

1040
00:46:20,880 --> 00:46:22,880
what's going on here

1041
00:46:22,880 --> 00:46:24,880
is in terms of a Lagrangian

1042
00:46:24,880 --> 00:46:26,880
or a terminal Lagrangian,

1043
00:46:26,880 --> 00:46:29,880
the Lagrangian describing this process here

1044
00:46:29,880 --> 00:46:32,880
describes one electron in,

1045
00:46:32,880 --> 00:46:33,880
one electron out,

1046
00:46:33,880 --> 00:46:35,880
and one photon out,

1047
00:46:35,880 --> 00:46:36,880
and so you build that

1048
00:46:36,880 --> 00:46:39,880
out of the field operators.

1049
00:46:39,880 --> 00:46:43,880
One electron in

1050
00:46:43,880 --> 00:46:45,880
is psi electron.

1051
00:46:45,880 --> 00:46:46,880
It creates...

1052
00:46:46,880 --> 00:46:49,880
It has the creation and annihilation operators in it.

1053
00:46:49,880 --> 00:46:51,880
An electron out

1054
00:46:51,880 --> 00:46:53,880
is psi dagger

1055
00:46:53,880 --> 00:46:54,880
of the electron,

1056
00:46:54,880 --> 00:46:55,880
and a photon emitted in it.

1057
00:46:56,880 --> 00:46:58,880
And a photon out

1058
00:46:58,880 --> 00:47:00,880
is the field operator for the photon.

1059
00:47:00,880 --> 00:47:01,880
And if you plug in

1060
00:47:01,880 --> 00:47:03,880
all the creation and annihilation operators,

1061
00:47:03,880 --> 00:47:04,880
you will find in here,

1062
00:47:04,880 --> 00:47:05,880
buried in here,

1063
00:47:05,880 --> 00:47:08,880
terms where a photon is emitted,

1064
00:47:08,880 --> 00:47:09,880
an electron absorbed,

1065
00:47:09,880 --> 00:47:11,880
another electron emitted,

1066
00:47:11,880 --> 00:47:12,880
and so forth.

1067
00:47:12,880 --> 00:47:14,880
And this codifies,

1068
00:47:14,880 --> 00:47:16,880
this describes

1069
00:47:16,880 --> 00:47:18,880
all of the various basic processes

1070
00:47:18,880 --> 00:47:21,880
that can happen in quantum electrodynamics.

1071
00:47:21,880 --> 00:47:24,880
Now, there's a parameter in the Lagrangian

1072
00:47:24,880 --> 00:47:25,880
that appears,

1073
00:47:25,880 --> 00:47:30,880
appears the electric charge of the electron,

1074
00:47:30,880 --> 00:47:32,880
and that, roughly speaking,

1075
00:47:32,880 --> 00:47:36,880
is associated with the amplitude

1076
00:47:36,880 --> 00:47:40,880
for a electron to emit a photon.

1077
00:47:40,880 --> 00:47:41,880
An electron,

1078
00:47:41,880 --> 00:47:42,880
let's say you hit the electron,

1079
00:47:42,880 --> 00:47:43,880
or whatever,

1080
00:47:43,880 --> 00:47:48,880
the electron plows into the side of a x-ray machine.

1081
00:47:48,880 --> 00:47:51,880
What's the probability that a photon will be emitted?

1082
00:47:51,880 --> 00:47:54,880
Well, the amplitude is the electric charge,

1083
00:47:54,880 --> 00:47:56,880
and the probability is proportional

1084
00:47:56,880 --> 00:47:58,880
to the square of the electric charge.

1085
00:47:58,880 --> 00:48:00,880
So all of this here

1086
00:48:00,880 --> 00:48:03,880
is a way of describing

1087
00:48:03,880 --> 00:48:06,880
all of these basic processes,

1088
00:48:06,880 --> 00:48:08,880
and when they're combined together,

1089
00:48:08,880 --> 00:48:09,880
they produce forces,

1090
00:48:09,880 --> 00:48:12,880
they produce processes where photons are emitted,

1091
00:48:12,880 --> 00:48:15,880
the whole world of quantum electrodynamics

1092
00:48:15,880 --> 00:48:16,880
flows out of this,

1093
00:48:16,880 --> 00:48:18,880
basically, one expression here.

1094
00:48:18,880 --> 00:48:21,880
We won't try to go through that again now.

1095
00:48:24,880 --> 00:48:27,380
But let's start adding a

1096
00:48:27,380 --> 00:48:29,880
little bit to our particle list.

1097
00:48:29,880 --> 00:48:31,880
The next particles of interest,

1098
00:48:31,880 --> 00:48:33,880
these are, of course, familiar to you, I'm sure.

1099
00:48:33,880 --> 00:48:35,880
Now, if this were 1960,

1100
00:48:35,880 --> 00:48:40,880
when I, well, I was,

