1962, when I went to graduate school,

1102
00:48:43,880 --> 00:48:45,880
probably the next particles I might write down

1103
00:48:45,880 --> 00:48:50,880
would be protons and neutrons.

1104
00:48:50,880 --> 00:48:53,880
Protons and neutrons are now subsumed

1105
00:48:53,880 --> 00:48:56,880
by quarks.

1106
00:48:56,880 --> 00:48:59,880
It is widely believed that in some sense,

1107
00:48:59,880 --> 00:49:03,880
protons and neutrons are composites of quarks,

1108
00:49:03,880 --> 00:49:06,880
although we will, remind me to come back

1109
00:49:06,880 --> 00:49:08,880
to this issue of the difference

1110
00:49:08,880 --> 00:49:11,880
or what it means to be composite versus elementary.

1111
00:49:11,880 --> 00:49:13,880
It's a very interesting story.

1112
00:49:13,880 --> 00:49:17,880
But naively, quarks are smaller than protons and neutrons,

1113
00:49:17,880 --> 00:49:20,880
and so protons and neutrons,

1114
00:49:20,880 --> 00:49:22,880
which are big fat globs,

1115
00:49:22,880 --> 00:49:25,880
are made up out of quarks.

1116
00:49:25,880 --> 00:49:28,880
So, next thing are quarks.

1117
00:49:28,880 --> 00:49:30,880
There's a lot of quarks.

1118
00:49:30,880 --> 00:49:33,880
We won't even get to all of them tonight

1119
00:49:33,880 --> 00:49:35,880
or the whole set of distinctions between them.

1120
00:49:35,880 --> 00:49:37,880
I don't think we will.

1121
00:49:37,880 --> 00:49:41,880
But there's more than one type of quark.

1122
00:49:41,880 --> 00:49:45,880
There are six types of quarks,

1123
00:49:45,880 --> 00:49:48,880
six distinct particles,

1124
00:49:48,880 --> 00:49:50,380
all of which are very similar

1125
00:49:50,380 --> 00:49:51,880
to each other in some respects,

1126
00:49:51,880 --> 00:49:54,880
very different from each other in other respects.

1127
00:49:54,880 --> 00:49:56,880
So let's list them.

1128
00:49:56,880 --> 00:49:58,880
There are...

1129
00:49:58,880 --> 00:50:00,880
They go under... They have names, all right?

1130
00:50:00,880 --> 00:50:02,880
Well, why are they called what they are?

1131
00:50:02,880 --> 00:50:05,880
They're called what they are just historically,

1132
00:50:05,880 --> 00:50:08,880
randomly people assigned silly names to them,

1133
00:50:08,880 --> 00:50:11,880
and there's no logic to what they're called,

1134
00:50:11,880 --> 00:50:13,880
no logic at all.

1135
00:50:13,880 --> 00:50:16,880
There's first of all the up quark,

1136
00:50:16,880 --> 00:50:18,880
and that's called U.

1137
00:50:18,880 --> 00:50:20,880
The symbol is U.

1138
00:50:20,880 --> 00:50:22,380
Well, let's see. We should

1139
00:50:22,380 --> 00:50:23,880
write there are quarks here. Quarks.

1140
00:50:25,880 --> 00:50:28,880
And I suppose the symbol for quarks is Q.

1141
00:50:28,880 --> 00:50:31,880
All quarks are fermions.

1142
00:50:31,880 --> 00:50:33,880
We'll write down their charge later.

1143
00:50:33,880 --> 00:50:37,880
They have all baryon number of one-third.

1144
00:50:37,880 --> 00:50:39,880
Now, why one-third?

1145
00:50:39,880 --> 00:50:41,880
Well, the reason is very simple.

1146
00:50:41,880 --> 00:50:44,880
The baryon number is basically the counting

1147
00:50:44,880 --> 00:50:47,880
of the number of protons and neutrons.

1148
00:50:47,880 --> 00:50:49,880
Each proton is counted

1149
00:50:49,880 --> 00:50:52,880
as having one unit of baryon number.

1150
00:50:52,880 --> 00:50:55,880
Each neutron is counted as having one unit of baryon.

1151
00:50:55,880 --> 00:50:58,880
Baryon is just a word for protons and neutrons

1152
00:50:58,880 --> 00:51:02,880
and a somewhat generalization of protons and neutrons.

1153
00:51:02,880 --> 00:51:06,880
Nucleon is a word for protons and neutrons.

1154
00:51:06,880 --> 00:51:08,880
There are other particles which we'll come to

1155
00:51:08,880 --> 00:51:11,880
which are very similar to protons and neutrons.

1156
00:51:11,880 --> 00:51:14,880
They're also called baryons.

1157
00:51:14,880 --> 00:51:17,880
The prefix bary, I think, means heavy.

1158
00:51:19,880 --> 00:51:22,380
And baryons, we'll call baryons because

1159
00:51:22,380 --> 00:51:24,880
they're a lot heavier than electrons.

1160
00:51:24,880 --> 00:51:28,880
But counting up the number of protons and neutrons,

1161
00:51:28,880 --> 00:51:30,880
what do you call the number

1162
00:51:30,880 --> 00:51:32,880
of protons plus neutrons in an atom?

1163
00:51:32,880 --> 00:51:34,880
The atomic weight.

1164
00:51:34,880 --> 00:51:37,880
Yeah, the atomic weight.

1165
00:51:37,880 --> 00:51:42,880
The atomic weight is equal, approximately equal,

1166
00:51:42,880 --> 00:51:45,880
to the total number of protons and neutrons.

1167
00:51:45,880 --> 00:51:47,880
And the total number of protons and neutrons is

1168
00:51:47,880 --> 00:51:49,880
equal to the total number of protons and neutrons.

1169
00:51:49,880 --> 00:51:51,380
So the number of protons and

1170
00:51:51,380 --> 00:51:52,880
neutrons in nuclear physics never changes.

1171
00:51:52,880 --> 00:51:54,880
Protons can turn into neutrons.

1172
00:51:54,880 --> 00:51:57,880
Neutrons can turn into protons plus other things.

1173
00:51:57,880 --> 00:52:02,880
But the number of protons plus neutrons never changes.

1174
00:52:02,880 --> 00:52:05,880
You have isotopes.

1175
00:52:05,880 --> 00:52:07,880
You do have isotopes.

1176
00:52:07,880 --> 00:52:09,880
But still, the number of

1177
00:52:09,880 --> 00:52:11,880
protons plus neutrons doesn't change.

1178
00:52:11,880 --> 00:52:13,880
The number of protons can change.

1179
00:52:13,880 --> 00:52:15,880
How can the number of protons change?

1180
00:52:15,880 --> 00:52:17,380
No, no, I'm just saying that

1181
00:52:17,380 --> 00:52:18,880
different isotopes have different numbers of neutrons.

1182
00:52:18,880 --> 00:52:20,880
Oh, yeah, indeed they do.

1183
00:52:20,880 --> 00:52:22,880
But are there processes where the

1184
00:52:22,880 --> 00:52:24,880
number of protons and neutrons change?

1185
00:52:24,880 --> 00:52:27,380
Protons, not plus neutrons, but

1186
00:52:27,380 --> 00:52:29,880
protons and or neutrons change?

1187
00:52:29,880 --> 00:52:31,880
Beta decay, radioactivity.

1188
00:52:31,880 --> 00:52:34,880
In radioactivity, one form of radioactivity,

1189
00:52:34,880 --> 00:52:38,380
a neutron decays into a proton

1190
00:52:38,380 --> 00:52:41,880
plus an electron and an antineutrino.

1191
00:52:41,880 --> 00:52:43,880
Okay, so in that process, the

1192
00:52:43,880 --> 00:52:45,880
number of protons changes by one,

1193
00:52:45,880 --> 00:52:47,880
the number of neutrons changes by one,

1194
00:52:47,880 --> 00:52:50,880
but the number of protons plus neutrons doesn't change.

1195
00:52:50,880 --> 00:52:53,380
There's a generalization of that in

1196
00:52:53,380 --> 00:52:55,880
all of nuclear physics and particle physics.

1197
00:52:55,880 --> 00:52:58,880
There's a certain quantity

1198
00:52:58,880 --> 00:53:01,880
which, for ordinary nuclear physics,

1199
00:53:01,880 --> 00:53:03,880
is just the number of protons plus neutrons,

1200
00:53:03,880 --> 00:53:08,880
and that number is sometimes called the baryon number.

1201
00:53:08,880 --> 00:53:10,880
We'll have to generalize it a

1202
00:53:10,880 --> 00:53:12,880
little bit beyond protons and neutrons.

1203
00:53:12,880 --> 00:53:14,880
It's the baryon number, and it could have

1204
00:53:14,880 --> 00:53:16,880
been defined to be two for the protons,

1205
00:53:16,880 --> 00:53:19,880
or seven for the protons, or pi for the protons,

1206
00:53:19,880 --> 00:53:21,880
but whatever it is, it has to be

1207
00:53:21,880 --> 00:53:23,880
defined as twice as much for two protons,

1208
00:53:23,880 --> 00:53:25,880
three times as much for three protons.

1209
00:53:25,880 --> 00:53:28,380
So it's a convention that you say

1210
00:53:28,380 --> 00:53:30,880
the baryon number of the proton is one.

1211
00:53:30,880 --> 00:53:34,880
Incidentally, what's the baryon number of the antiproton?

1212
00:53:34,880 --> 00:53:36,880
Minus one.

1213
00:53:36,880 --> 00:53:38,880
Minus one.

1214
00:53:38,880 --> 00:53:41,380
Proton has baryon number plus

1215
00:53:41,380 --> 00:53:43,880
one, antiproton, baryon number minus one.

1216
00:53:43,880 --> 00:53:45,880
Neutron, baryon number minus one.

1217
00:53:46,880 --> 00:53:49,880
Antineutron, baryon number minus one.

1218
00:53:49,880 --> 00:53:52,380
But clearly there's an element of

1219
00:53:52,380 --> 00:53:54,880
convention in exactly what you call them.

1220
00:53:54,880 --> 00:53:56,880
But once it was fixed that the

1221
00:53:56,880 --> 00:53:58,880
baryon number of a proton was one,

1222
00:53:58,880 --> 00:54:01,880
then the baryon number of a quark was a third,

1223
00:54:01,880 --> 00:54:05,880
because three quarks make a proton.

1224
00:54:05,880 --> 00:54:09,380
So it's just a historical glitch that the baryon

1225
00:54:09,380 --> 00:54:12,880
number of the most fundamental thing in nuclear physics

1226
00:54:12,880 --> 00:54:14,880
is one third and not one.

1227
00:54:14,880 --> 00:54:16,880
What about an antiquark?

1228
00:54:16,880 --> 00:54:18,880
There are antiquarks.

1229
00:54:18,880 --> 00:54:21,880
Baryon number is minus a third.

1230
00:54:21,880 --> 00:54:23,880
So I won't write that down separately.

1231
00:54:23,880 --> 00:54:27,880
The number of quarks is conserved?

1232
00:54:27,880 --> 00:54:30,380
Number of quarks minus the

1233
00:54:30,380 --> 00:54:32,880
number of antiquarks is conserved.

1234
00:54:32,880 --> 00:54:37,880
Now, whether or not that is an absolute conservation law,

1235
00:54:37,880 --> 00:54:41,880
it is not believed to be an absolute conservation law.

1236
00:54:41,880 --> 00:54:43,880
What do I mean by absolute conservation law?

1237
00:54:43,880 --> 00:54:45,880
Can a proton disappear?

1238
00:54:45,880 --> 00:54:47,880
It can't completely disappear.

1239
00:54:47,880 --> 00:54:49,880
Its energy has to go someplace.

1240
00:54:49,880 --> 00:54:53,880
Are there processes in nature where a proton might disappear

1241
00:54:53,880 --> 00:54:55,880
and become something that is

1242
00:54:55,880 --> 00:54:57,880
neither a proton nor a neutron

1243
00:54:57,880 --> 00:55:00,880
or anything else that you would call a baryon?

1244
00:55:00,880 --> 00:55:04,880
For example, without violating charge conservation,

1245
00:55:04,880 --> 00:55:09,880
a proton could become a positron and a photon.

1246
00:55:09,880 --> 00:55:12,380
So a proton could decay

1247
00:55:12,380 --> 00:55:14,880
into a positron and a photon.

1248
00:55:14,880 --> 00:55:15,880
Does it?

1249
00:55:15,880 --> 00:55:16,880
Well, you can wait.

1250
00:55:16,880 --> 00:55:18,380
If you have a single proton

1251
00:55:18,380 --> 00:55:19,880
and you sit there and wait,

1252
00:55:19,880 --> 00:55:22,380
you will wait a long,

1253
00:55:22,380 --> 00:55:24,880
long time before that proton decays.

1254
00:55:24,880 --> 00:55:29,380
Its half-life to decay that way is at least

1255
00:55:29,380 --> 00:55:33,880
10 to the 33 or 10 to the 34 years.

1256
00:55:33,880 --> 00:55:37,880
So this is not something that happens very regularly.

1257
00:55:37,880 --> 00:55:40,880
Does it happen at all?

1258
00:55:40,880 --> 00:55:42,880
The thinking is yes, it does,

1259
00:55:42,880 --> 00:55:44,880
but this is one of the

1260
00:55:44,880 --> 00:55:46,880
very, very interesting questions of particle physics

1261
00:55:46,880 --> 00:55:49,880
of whether the proton can decay.

1262
00:55:49,880 --> 00:55:50,880
And when you say can it decay,

1263
00:55:50,880 --> 00:55:53,880
you mean decay into something that

1264
00:55:53,880 --> 00:55:56,880
does not carry a baryon number.

1265
00:55:56,880 --> 00:55:59,880
And it is widely believed that the answer is yes,

1266
00:55:59,880 --> 00:56:01,880
but it has never been demonstrated.

1267
00:56:01,880 --> 00:56:04,380
Incidentally, how do you wait around for 10

1268
00:56:04,380 --> 00:56:06,880
to the 34 years for a proton to decay?

1269
00:56:06,880 --> 00:56:09,380
You get 10 to the 34 protons

1270
00:56:09,380 --> 00:56:11,880
and you wait around for one of them

1271
00:56:11,880 --> 00:56:13,880
and you see one.

1272
00:56:13,880 --> 00:56:15,880
Now 10 to the 34

1273
00:56:15,880 --> 00:56:17,880
protons is a lot of protons.

1274
00:56:17,880 --> 00:56:20,880
If you have protons and antiprotons together.

1275
00:56:20,880 --> 00:56:22,880
No, that's not that.

1276
00:56:22,880 --> 00:56:25,380
That's zero baryon number because

1277
00:56:25,380 --> 00:56:27,880
it goes to zero baryon number.

1278
00:56:27,880 --> 00:56:29,880
A proton has baryon number one.

1279
00:56:29,880 --> 00:56:31,880
An antiproton has baryon number minus one.

1280
00:56:31,880 --> 00:56:34,880
So that's not a baryon.

1281
00:56:34,880 --> 00:56:37,880
We call them baryon-violating processes,

1282
00:56:37,880 --> 00:56:41,880
processes in which the baryon number is not conserved.

1283
00:56:41,880 --> 00:56:45,380
Nobody has ever witnessed such a process

1284
00:56:45,380 --> 00:56:48,880
in the laboratory or any place else.

1285
00:56:48,880 --> 00:56:51,880
Can they happen?

1286
00:56:51,880 --> 00:56:53,380
There does not seem to be

1287
00:56:53,380 --> 00:56:54,880
any reason why they cannot happen

1288
00:56:54,880 --> 00:56:57,880
built into the mathematics of what we know.

1289
00:56:57,880 --> 00:56:59,880
So we leave this as an open question,

1290
00:56:59,880 --> 00:57:02,380
but empirically and at least

1291
00:57:02,380 --> 00:57:04,880
to a very, very high precision,

1292
00:57:04,880 --> 00:57:07,880
baryon number is conserved and quarks by

1293
00:57:07,880 --> 00:57:10,880
definition have one third of a unit.

1294
00:57:10,880 --> 00:57:11,880
One third of a unit.

1295
00:57:11,880 --> 00:57:12,880
That's the number one,

1296
00:57:12,880 --> 00:57:14,880
minus a third for antiquarks.

1297
00:57:14,880 --> 00:57:16,880
But in order to fill in the rest of this,

1298
00:57:16,880 --> 00:57:19,880
in particular electric charge and mass,

1299
00:57:19,880 --> 00:57:21,380
we have to label which

1300
00:57:21,380 --> 00:57:22,880
kind of quark we're talking about.

1301
00:57:22,880 --> 00:57:25,880
And there are lots of different kinds of quarks.

1302
00:57:25,880 --> 00:57:27,380
So let's put in the

1303
00:57:27,380 --> 00:57:28,880
